english:
  title: Reply to a Mongol Official
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this response. In this month, I suddenly received your esteemed directive. The great office has journeyed a thousand miles to reach our humble borders, and in your first letter you have shown us such grace—I am deeply moved with joy and gratitude.

    Yet the matters you inquire about are not truly the intention of our realm, and I fear them greatly. I dare to lay bare my heart, hoping only for your magnanimous forbearance.

    Regarding what you mention—that we spoke fair words and, after you withdrew, we turned back in treachery, fleeing into hiding; that those unworthy men Song Lip-jang and Heo Gong-jae spread lies—our nation has long maintained intimate relations with yours. When Song Lip-jang came and spoke of how your great powers would soon raise armies to conquer us, his words held such weight that our people heard them and were seized with terror. Half fled in panic, and our cities stood nearly empty. For when thunder rolls across the heavens, all beneath tremble alike. Thus I too could not help but fear. Worried that our remaining people would all scatter and disappear, I dreaded we could not fulfill our annual tribute, nor continue to serve the great nation. So with what few remained, we sought only to survive in the deep mists and unhealthy lands. How could I harbor other thoughts? Heaven and earth itself witness this truth.

    As for your words about the Darughachi—if he died, he died; yet now you say we bound him—that official who remains in our capital has been treated with great care and respect, never given offense. Has not your great nation heard of this? And we commanded throughout our cities that all be received with generous treatment. If among them some fell short of your expectations, I could not know every detail. I trust your wise nation will examine this fairly. That we would dare to seize an envoy of yours—such a thing is impossible. You may later verify this and know the truth.

    You say we should have submitted with sincere hearts and come out to welcome you—that we came instead with soldiers to resist. Now your great army is revealed upon the plain. Though your mighty nation need not speak of it, our small realm knows that courtesy demands we come ourselves to receive and honor you. Yet our removal to this distant, remote place was not by your command, and looking back, I cannot be without fault. So ashamed and afraid, I have not been prompt in presenting myself. But know that our heart of submission is one and the same—how could there be two?

    Though our small nation is ignorant and unenlightened, we understand the duty to fear and obey the great powers. Our reverence for you extends back many years—how could we raise rebellion now?

    I humbly beseech you: examine all this clearly, forgive our failings, cherish the small, and preserve our distant realm. This is my true wish.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Darughachi (達魯花赤): A Mongol administrative official. The text''s reference to binding or executing such an official was a serious accusation of rebellion.'
  - key: ''
    value: The letter appears to respond to multiple accusations of disloyalty, addressing each charge systematically—a common rhetorical strategy in diplomatic correspondence of the period.
  - key: ''
    value: The mention of fleeing to 'deep mists and unhealthy lands' may refer to the movement of the Korean court to resist Mongol pressure, a historical event reflected in this letter.
